# Git & PowerShell Conventions

This workspace runs on Windows with PowerShell. All git commands must avoid bash-only syntax.

## Commit Messages

**Never use heredoc** (`<<'EOF'`) — PowerShell does not support it.

Use one of these approaches instead:

### Multi `-m` flags (preferred for short messages)
```powershell
git commit -m "fix: summary line" -m "- Detail one" -m "- Detail two"
```

### Temp file (preferred for long or complex messages)
```powershell
@"
fix: summary line

- Detail one with "quotes" and special chars
- Detail two
"@ | Set-Content -Path ".git/COMMIT_MSG" -Encoding utf8
git commit -F ".git/COMMIT_MSG"
Remove-Item ".git/COMMIT_MSG"
```

## Other Rules

- **Quote paths** with double quotes: `git add "path with spaces/file.ts"`
- **Do not use** `&&` to chain commands — use `;` or separate calls instead, since `&&` requires PowerShell 7+.
- **Do not use** `$(...)` bash-style command substitution in git arguments.

## PR thread replies (PowerShell + gh)

- **Use the pull-review-comments create endpoint with JSON input** for in-thread replies:
```powershell
$payload = '{"body":"Fixed — ...","in_reply_to":1234567890}'
$payload | gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls/{pr_number}/comments --method POST --input -
```
- **Treat immediate `404` replies after push as non-fatal**: this commonly means the conversation auto-resolved/outdated before the reply posted.
- **Still post the top-level PR summary comment** even when one or more thread replies race and 404.

## Worktree gotchas (Windows)

- **`gh pr merge --delete-branch` fails when the PR head branch is checked out in a worktree.** The remote merge still succeeds, but the local-branch deletion errors out with `cannot delete branch '<name>' used by worktree at '<path>'`. After the failure, verify the merge succeeded with `gh pr view <num> --json state,mergedAt` and clean up the local branch manually after pruning the worktree.
- **Avoid `cd` into a worktree path whose branch is also the active branch in another window**, since git refuses to operate on the same branch from two checkouts.
- **Before `git worktree remove` or `Remove-Item -Recurse -Force` on a worktree directory, kill any process holding file handles inside it** (Node, vitest watcher, esbuild, VS Code/Cursor windows pointed at the worktree). Otherwise both commands fail with `Permission denied` / `The process cannot access the file because it is being used by another process` and you end up with an orphaned dir even though `git worktree prune` cleans up the bookkeeping.
- **List worktrees first with `git worktree list`** so you know what to clean up; clean orphaned dirs only after the holding process is gone.
